<div id=3D"description-of-the-algorithm" class=3D"anchor skill-heading coll=
apsed" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=
=3D"true">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Description of the Algorithm</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-description-of-the-algorithm=
"><div class=3D"section-container">

<p>Together Alice and Bob choose a large prime number \(p\) and a number \(=
g\) such that \(1 &lt; g &lt;p.\) (Usually \(g\) is chosen to be quite smal=
l, for ease of computation.) These numbers do not need to be secret, so the=
y can be communicated freely over a public channel. Alice secretly chooses =
an integer \(n,\) and Bob secretly chooses an integer \(m.\)</p>

<p>Now Alice sends Bob the number \( g^n \pmod p,\) and Bob sends Alice \( =
g^m \pmod p.\)</p>

<p>Using her secret \(n,\) Alice computes \(s \equiv (g^{m})^{n} \equiv g^{=
mn}  \pmod{p}.\) Using his secret \(m,\) Bob computes \(s \equiv (g^{n})^{m=
} \equiv g^{mn}  \pmod{p}.\) Now Alice and Bob have a secret key \( s\) kno=
wn only to them, which can be used to send messages via any number of secur=
e private-key cryptosystems. </p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Let \( p =3D 191\) and \(g=3D2.\) Suppose Alice picks \( 42\) and Bob picks=
 \( 33.\) Then Alice computes \( 2^{42} \equiv 20 \pmod{191}\) and Bob comp=
utes \( 2^{33} \equiv 103 \pmod{191}.\) They send the results of these comp=
utations to each other. Upon receiving \( 103,\) Alice computes \( 103^{42}=
 \equiv 115 \pmod{191},\) and Bob computes \( 20^{33} \equiv 115 \pmod{191}=
.\) So they have a key that they have agreed on without disclosing their se=
cret numbers to each other. They can use this key to communicate securely v=
ia a cryptosystem of their choosing.
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"discrete-log-problem" class=3D"anchor skill-heading collapsed" d=
ata-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=3D"true=
">
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Discrete Log Problem</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-discrete-log-problem"><div c=
lass=3D"section-container">

<p>An eavesdropper (often called Eve) will see the results of any transmiss=
ions over public channels, so she will know \( p,g,g^n \pmod{p},\) and \(g^=
m \pmod{p}.\) Her goal is to compute \( g^{mn} \pmod p.\) If she can comput=
e \( m\) and \(n,\) then she has the same information as Alice and Bob and =
hence can read their messages. Computing the exponent \( n\) is like taking=
 a "mod-\(p\) base-\(g\) logarithm" of \( g^n,\) but this is expected to be=
 a hard problem in general. It is known as the <strong>discrete log problem=
</strong>. There is no known algorithm for efficiently computing discrete l=
ogs \(\pmod p\) in general.</p>

<p>It is also widely believed that there is no faster way for Eve to comput=
e \( g^{mn} \pmod p\) than by finding \(m\) and \(n,\) so that the security=
 of the Diffie-Hellman protocol is as strong as the difficulty of the discr=
ete log problem. </p>

<blockquote class=3D"example"><p>
Continuing the above example, Eve knows \( p=3D191,\) \( g=3D2,\) \( 2^n \e=
quiv 20 \pmod{191},\) and \( 2^m \equiv 103\pmod{191}.\) Without access to =
\(m=3D33\) or \(n=3D42,\) she will be unable to use this information to ded=
uce the shared key \( 115.\)
</p><!-- end-example --></blockquote>

</div>
</div>

<div id=3D"choosing-parameters" class=3D"anchor skill-heading collapsed" da=
ta-controller=3D"app/wiki:expandOrCollapse" data-controller-inited=3D"true"=
>
    <header class=3D"section-header">
        <span class=3D"css-sprite-chevrons chevron"></span>
        <h2>Choosing Parameters</h2>

       =20
    </header>
</div>

<div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-choosing-parameters"><div cl=
ass=3D"section-container">

<p>Certain choices of \( p\) and \( g\) are better than others. Here are so=
me guidelines that avoid common insecurities and attacks in the protocol.</=
p>

<p>(1) <strong>The prime \( p\) should be chosen so that the largest prime =
factor of \( p-1\) is large.</strong> If \( p-1 =3D q_1^{a_1}\cdots q_k^{a_=
k},\) where the \( q_i \) are all small primes, then an attack called the <=
a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/pohlig-hellman-algorithm/" class=3D"wi=
ki_link" title=3D"Pohlig-Hellman algorithm" target=3D"_blank">Pohlig-Hellma=
n algorithm</a> computes the discrete log \(x\) of \( g^x\) by using the <a=
 href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/chinese-remainder-theorem/" class=3D"wi=
ki_link" title=3D"Chinese remainder theorem" target=3D"_blank">Chinese rema=
inder theorem</a> and quickly computing \( x\) mod \( q_i^{a_i}.\)</p>

<p>For this reason, it is common to select values of \(p\) of the form \( p=
=3D2q+1,\) where \( q\) is a prime (called a <a href=3D"https://brilliant.o=
rg/wiki/fermats-last-theorem/#sophie-germains-work" class=3D"wiki_link" tit=
le=3D"Sophie Germain prime" target=3D"_blank">Sophie Germain prime</a>). Su=
ch \(p\) are often called <em>safe primes</em> due to the security of the p=
ublic keys based on arithmetic mod \(p.\)</p>

<p>(2) <strong>The base \( g\) should be chosen so that \(g\) has large <a =
href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/order-of-an-element/" class=3D"wiki_link=
" title=3D"order" target=3D"_blank">order</a>,</strong> i.e. \( g\) generat=
es a large subgroup of the multiplicative <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/=
wiki/group-theory-introduction/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"group" target=
=3D"_blank">group</a> \( ({\mathbb Z}/p{\mathbb Z})^*.\) This is so that an=
 attacker cannot find a discrete log of \( g^m\) by enumerating all the pos=
sibilities for \( g^m\) \((\)it also increases the number of possible secre=
t keys \( g^{mn}).\) When \(p=3D2q+1\) is a safe prime, \( g\) is often cho=
sen to have order \(q;\) the following exercise explains why this is prefer=
red to order \(2q =3D p-1:\)</p>

<p></p><div class=3D"problem-modal-container anchor" id=3D"problem-diffie-h=
ellman-and-the-last-bit">

    <div class=3D"wiki-problem" data-controller=3D"app/wiki:wikiShowProblem=
Answer" data-controller-inited=3D"true">

